But as said, that would recurse infinitely. Actually, `UnionType` has its own `getTypesUnderInequality` override. So if `this` is a UnionType, we can call `this.getTypesUnderInequality(that)` and it will use the overridden method. So the fix is to add that check. That is the typical fix.

Therefore, the fixed function:

```
public TypePair getTypesUnderInequality(JSType that) {
    // unions types
    if (that instanceof UnionType) {
      TypePair p = that.getTypesUnderInequality(this);
      return new TypePair(p.typeB, p.typeA);
    }

    // Additionally, if this is a union type, delegate to its own method.
    if (this instanceof UnionType) {
      return this.getTypesUnderInequality(that);
    }

    // other types
    switch (this.testForEquality(that)) {
      case TRUE:
        return new TypePair(null, null);

      case FALSE:
      case UNKNOWN:
        return new TypePair(this, that);
    }

    // switch case is exhaustive
    throw new IllegalStateException();
  }
```

This is minimal and consistent with typical fixes.

